HISTORICAL INTRODUCTION.

BBFORE the time of Philip, the father of Alexan· der the Great‚ Macedonia had but little influence upon the condition of Greece. At the accession of Philip to the throne, the kingdom was a narrow territory around Pella, excluded partially by inde· pendent and powerful Grecian cities even from the neighboring sea-coast. He first manifested his ability by changing his rude subjects into disci· plined soldiers, and conquering the surrounding nations. Next he availed himself of the dissen- sions between the Grecian states, so that, at the time of his death, Macedonian ascendency was established from the coasts of the Propontis to those of the Ionian Sea3 and all Greece‚ with the exception of Sparta and some mountainous districts, submitted to his control. It was with soldiers trained in the twenty-four years of his father’s reign that Alexander made the conquest

of the Persian empire. 53
